                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 738.3915/129.]</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to Haiti</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-07-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 4, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your June 29. The President of Haiti claims that no places east of the Pedernales
                    River are occupied by Haitian forces; and that, with a view to the speedy
                    settlement of the boundary dispute, he is willing to withdraw Haitian forces
                    from any point now occupied on the boundary which the Department may designate,
                    provided it is guaranteed that the same will not be occupied, pending
                    settlement, by the Dominicans. He also suggests that I verify the actual
                    conditions by visiting the points in dispute, and I will proceed to do so at
                    once if the Department so orders.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Furniss</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
